============================================================
Regional Disparities in Maternal Mortality (2023)
============================================================

Table 1. Global Distribution of Maternal Deaths by Region
------------------------------------------------------------
Region                         Share     Deaths     Key Drivers
------------------------------------------------------------
Sub-Saharan Africa              ~70%      ~182,000   Weak health systems, low skilled birth attendance,
                                                     high fertility, poverty
Southern Asia                   ~17%      ~43,000    Unequal access to care, rural poverty,
                                                     delayed referrals
Latin America & Caribbean       ~6%       ~15,000    Inequality, fragmented health systems
Europe & North America          ~3%       ~8,000     Low overall risk, internal disparities
Other Regions                   ~4%       ~12,000    Mixed system capacity
------------------------------------------------------------
GLOBAL TOTAL                    100%      ~260,000   Structural global inequality
------------------------------------------------------------


Table 2. Economic Disparities in Maternal Mortality
------------------------------------------------------------
Country Income Group        MMR (per 100,000)   Relative Risk
------------------------------------------------------------
Low-income countries        ~346                >30× higher risk
Lower-middle income         ~174                ~15×
Upper-middle income         ~67                 ~6×
High-income countries       ~10                 Baseline
------------------------------------------------------------


Table 3. Countries with Very High Maternal Mortality (MMR > 500)
------------------------------------------------------------
Country              MMR    Uncertainty Interval     Deaths        Main Factors
------------------------------------------------------------
Nigeria               993    718–1,540               ~75,000        Workforce shortages, poverty,
                                                                   high fertility
Chad                  748    493–1,248               High           Limited obstetric access
Central African Rep.  692    333–1,299               High           Fragile, conflict-affected system
South Sudan           692    400–1,254               High           Conflict-driven mortality
Liberia               628    436–913                 Moderate–High  Post-conflict recovery
Somalia               563    244–1,089               High           Chronic instability
Afghanistan           521    339–942                 High           Restricted maternal services
Benin                ~505    —                       High           System capacity gaps
Guinea-Bissau        ~518    —                       High           Limited service coverage
------------------------------------------------------------


Table 4. WHO Maternal Mortality Classification
------------------------------------------------------------
Category        MMR Range (per 100,000 live births)
------------------------------------------------------------
Very High       500–999
High            300–499
Moderate        100–299
Low             <100
------------------------------------------------------------


Table 5. High-Income & OECD Countries
------------------------------------------------------------
Country / Group     MMR     Notes
------------------------------------------------------------
Iceland             <3      Lowest globally
Ireland             <3      Strong obstetric care
Norway              <3      Universal maternal services
Denmark             <3      High-quality perinatal care
Switzerland         <3      Strong prevention systems
Italy               <3      Low maternal mortality
OECD Average        ~10.3   Benchmark
Colombia            ~59.5   Highest among OECD
Mexico              ~44     Above OECD average
------------------------------------------------------------


Table 6. United States – Developed Country Outlier
------------------------------------------------------------
Indicator                           Value
------------------------------------------------------------
Maternal mortality rate             ~19–22
Comparison to peers                 Higher than Canada, UK,
                                    South Korea, Western Europe
Key disparities                     Race/ethnicity, income,
                                    insurance, state policies
Structural drivers                  Fragmented care,
                                    inequitable access,
                                    chronic disease
------------------------------------------------------------


Table 7. Global Trends in Maternal Mortality (2000–2023)
------------------------------------------------------------
Year        Global MMR        Change
------------------------------------------------------------
2000        ~328              Baseline
2015        ~216              Rapid decline period
2023        ~197              ~40% decline from 2000
2030 SDG    <70               Off track
------------------------------------------------------------


Key Takeaways
------------------------------------------------------------
Insight                                    Implication
------------------------------------------------------------
Maternal mortality is concentrated         Sub-Saharan Africa is
                                           the global epicenter
Economic inequality dominates risk          Income level predicts survival
High-MMR countries drive global averages    Targeting them yields
                                           the largest gains
High-income countries are not immune        Internal inequality matters
Progress slowed after 2016                  SDG 3.1 unlikely without
                                           major acceleration
